Of the seventeen texts set in the book, four (plus one adaptation, see below) are by Battista Guarini, three by G.B. Strozzi the Elder, one each by Ridolfo Arlotti (c. 1550–1613), Livio Celiano, Antonio Ongaro (c. 1560–1592/1599),
Interestingly, Ongaro had enjoined the patronage, among others, of Girolamo Ruiz, dedicatee of Marenzio’s Book IV a 5 (1584). See Donatella Manzoli, “Ongaro, Antonio”, in Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani, vol. 79 (Rome: Istituto della Enciclopedia italiana, 2013; on line at http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/antonio-ongaro_(Dizionario-Biografico)/, accessed August 25, 2014). and Torquato Tasso; one text each is furthermore attributed to Bonifazio Bevilacqua and Annibale Caro, while three texts remain anonymous (see Table 1).
For more details about the attributions, see “The poetic texts: edition and critical report”. Three aspects are remarkable: the absence of Petrarca and Sannazaro (which together accounted for fifteen texts out of twenty-one in Book I a 4 of 1585 and for eleven texts out of fifteen in the Book for 4, 5, and 6 voices of 1588);
They were, however, absent already from Book V a 6 of 1591. the presence of Strozzi, which, in spite of previous settings by Marenzio,
In Book III a 6 (1585) and Book IV a 6 (1587). is probably to refer to the appearance, in 1593, of a posthumous edition of his Madrigali;
All the three text set by Marenzio were included in that collection (see “The poetic texts: edition and critical report”), which, according to James Chater, “momentarily revived” interest in Strozzi’s poetry among composers: see James Chater, “Family Matters: Music in the Life and Poetry of Giovambattista Strozzi the Elder” in Perspectives on Luca Marenzio’s Secular Music, ed. by Mauro Calcagno (Turnhout: Centre d’études supérieures de la Renaissance-Brepols, 2014), 75–140: 93 and 105. Chater also suggests that Marenzio’s Florentine connections, namely the families of Piero Strozzi and Gino Capponi, could help explain his “easy access to Florentine poetry” (104). and the first occurrences of Livio Celiano (Angelo Grillo) and Antonio Ongaro, whose poems Marenzio will set again in the last books a 5 of the late 1590s.
